&lt;html&gt;
Thank you for your kind reply.
&lt;p&gt;David Roussel wrote:
&lt;blockquote TYPE=CITE&gt;&nbsp;&lt;span 
class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;Mike,&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span 
class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;If
you only use your own tag libraries then you should have no problem running
JSPs with mock objects, although there are quite a few interfaces to implement.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span 
class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;We
use a small set of custom tags extensively to a give us a look and feel
on all our pages.&nbsp; We don&#39;t seem to have found any performance problems.&nbsp;
My only advise here is that if you are using weblogic then it&#39;s best to
manually remove references to beans from the request and response scope
after a page has been generated, or they won&#39;t be garbage collected.&nbsp;
But think I am starting to go off-topic...&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span 
class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;One
approach that can be used is to implement the RequestDispatcher of your
mock Servlet container such that when you can intercept forwards and includes.&nbsp;
This way you can assert that the Servlet has added the correct beans to
the request so that the JSP can render the correct view.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span 
class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span 
class=720445115-18062001&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Arial&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#0000FF&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;Dave&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;OutlookMessageHeader&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Tahoma&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;-----Original
Message-----&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Tahoma&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;&lt;b&gt;From:&lt;/b&gt; Mike Duffy [&lt;A HREF=&quot;mailto:mike.duffy@...&quot;&gt;mailto:mike.duffy@...&lt;/A&gt;]&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Tahoma&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Sent:&lt;/b&gt; 18 June 2001 16:46&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Tahoma&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;&lt;b&gt;To:&lt;/b&gt; junit@yahoogroups.com&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Tahoma&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=-1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Subject:&lt;/b&gt; Re: [junit] Re: Has
someone done Servlet JUnit tests?&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;tt&gt;Yes, keeping servlets and JSPs as thin as possible is a good approach.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Is anyone aware of any problems with the implementation of JSP tag
libraries on the various application servers?&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Also, is there any significant hit to performance when using tag
libraries?&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Mike&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;
&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Paul Hodgetts wrote:&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; Peter Qi wrote:&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &gt; I need to create some JUnit tests for a Servlet.&nbsp;
But because the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &gt; doGet(HttpServletRequest, HttpServletResponse) and&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &gt; doPost(HttpServletRequest, HttpServletResponse) methods
have no returns,&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &gt; and HttpServletRequest and HttpServletResponse are generated
by the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &gt; system, I could not create JUnit tests for them.&nbsp;
Does anyone have some&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &gt; experience?&nbsp; Thanks a lot for the help.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; You can use HTTPUnit to run tests against the servlet.&nbsp;
The&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; problem, however, as you point out, is that you only have&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; limited visibility into the servlet, since you can only check&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; the returned HTTP response to the web client.&nbsp; It&#39;s gets
even&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; more fun when you&#39;re trying to test the behavior of session&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; time outs, security and log in checks, etc.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; What we&#39;ve discussed doing is to make our servlets (and JSPs&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; via tag libraries) very thin layers that take the incoming&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; requests and just delegate to our presentation helper classes.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; In many cases, we&#39;ll end up just passing the request and&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; session objects along, but we now have a point where we can&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; create the request or session objects in particular states&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; (like expired session), so we can much more easily test the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; interface&#39;s behavior, plus we can use JUnit.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; This isn&#39;t a silver bullet or anything, because there are&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; still cases where you want to test the actual returned HTML,&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; and sometimes HTTPUnit tests are the best way to do that.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; But it seems like it will make our life a bit easier for some&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; other classes of presentation layer testing.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; Anyone else try this?&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; -Paul Hodgetts&lt;/tt&gt;
